{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491567"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:53:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:53:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"985"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/985"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.19,0.09,0.23,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"985"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68021"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/985"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"985"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53486"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"256"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4046"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9067"},{"type":"tags","id":"9084"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9531"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14794"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68021"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents with a three-week history of anorexia, weight loss and gradual onset of a dull, generalised abdominal pain. Over the last three days she had become jaundiced, with dark urine and pale stools. Four days ago, she returned from a one-week trip to visit her family in Malaysia. As they live in an endemic region, she had been taking proguanil for prevention of malaria. On examination her blood pressure is 115/70 mmHg, pulse 90/min and temperature 37.2C. She is obviously jaundiced and the rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. The liver function test results are:-\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin\u00a0 293\u00b5mol/L (\u0026lt;25)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlkaline phosphatase (ALP) 1914U/L (40-130)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGamma glutamyl transpeptidase (GGT) 859U/L (\u0026lt;50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum alanine transaminase (ALT) 361U/L (\u0026lt;51)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum albumin 31g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most likely cause of her illness?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carcinoma of the pancreas","Viral hepatitis","Choledocholithiasis","Drug-induced cholestasis","Liver abscess"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical and biochemical picture is that of an (obstructive or cholestatic) conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia. The anorexia, abdominal pain and weight loss are highly suggestive of a malignant cause even with the short time period, with \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eof\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ethe\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreas\u003C/strong\u003E being the most likely diagnosis.  Whilst painless jaundice may be a textbook typical sign of pancreatic cancer, it does not exclude the diagnosis as the pain can be caused by obstruction by the cancer.  The subtle signs of pancreatic cancer makes it difficult to detect early. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral hepatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is more common in developing countries, and this woman may have been exposed during her holiday. However, the time frame of symptoms is inconsistent with an infection as she was symptomatic before her trip. \u003Cstrong\u003ECholedocholithiasis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with RUQ or epigastric pain which may be transient in nature. Proguanil is associated with hepatotoxicity, however the timeframe and symptoms are not consistent with an adverse effect of a medication which was commenced less than two weeks ago. While a \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver abscess\u003C/strong\u003E may cause jaundice with associated anorexia and weight loss, almost all patients with a liver abscess present with a fever as the predominant symptom which is not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anorexia, weight loss and jaundice in an older patient should be attributed to carcinoma of the pancreas until proven otherwise."],"references":["Roche SP, Kobos R. Jaundice in the adult patient. Am Fam Physician. 2004 Jan 15;69(2):299-304. PMID: 14765767. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14765767/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53486"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"985"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53486"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-08T14:39:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-08T14:39:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"985"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68021"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeading